SIMPLE: incendiary
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Incendiary
<hw>In*cen"di*a*ry</hw> <pr>(?; 277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>;
<plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Incendiaries</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L.
<ets>incendiarius</ets>: cf. F. <ets>incendiaire</ets>. See
<er>Incense</er> to inflame.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Any person who maliciously sets fire to a building
or other valuable or other valuable property.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A person who excites or inflames factions, and
promotes quarrels or sedition; an agitator; an exciter.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Several cities . . . drove them out as
<qex>incendiaries</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Bentley.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Incendiary</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Incendiary
<hw>In*cen"di*a*ry</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>incendiarius</ets>,
fr. <ets>incendium</ets> a fire, conflagration: cf. F.
<ets>incendiaire</ets>. See <er>Incense</er> to inflame.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to incendiarism, or the malicious
burning of valuable property; <as>as, <ex>incendiary</ex> material; as
<ex>incendiary</ex> crime.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Tending to excite or inflame factions, sedition, or
quarrel; inflammatory; seditious.</def> <rj><au>Paley.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Incendiary device</b></col>, <cd>a device designed to set
a structure on fire; a firebomb.</cd> -- <col><b>Incendiary
shell</b></col>, <cd>a bombshell. See <er>Carcass</er>, 4.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Incendious</ent>⟦br⟧
